The paper focuses on the development of a fully autonomous rotorcraft UAS for long-term observation missions, which involves the integration of robotics, computer vision, and machine learning technologies. Therefore, cs.RO (Robotics) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of vision-based precision landing for automated energy replenishment, which falls under the scope of cs.CV (Computer Vision). The implementation of high-level autonomous decision making using state machines and the evaluation of landing pad pose estimation accuracy suggest the involvement of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.SY (Systems and Control). Finally, the paper provides an extensive evaluation of the system's performance, which may involve statistical analysis and machine learning techniques, indicating the relevance of cs.LG (Machine Learning).
